'''Denis Lemi Zakaria Lako Lado''' (born 20 November 1996) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for {{French football updater|Monaco}} club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], whom he [[Captain (association football)|captains]], and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]]. He has also represented Switzerland internationally at youth level.

==Club career==

=== Servette ===
Born in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, to a South Sudanese father and a Congolese mother,<ref name="zackig">{{cite news|last1=Wuillemin|first1=Dominic|date=3 October 2015|title=Zackig|language=de|work=[[Berner Zeitung]]|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/zackig/story/11694896|access-date=9 June 2017}}</ref> he first began playing for local club [[Servette FC|Servette]].<ref name=":0" />

===Young Boys===
Zakaria joined [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]] in June 2015 for an undisclosed fee, signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=U19-Nationalspieler Zakaria zu den Young Boys|url=http://www.bernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/U19Nationalspieler-Zakaria-zu-den-Young-Boys/story/19998651|access-date=9 June 2017|work=[[Berner Zeitung]]|date=26 June 2015|language=de}}</ref> He made his [[Swiss Super League]] debut on 18 July 2015 against [[FC Zürich]] in 1–1 away draw replacing [[Alexander Gerndt]] after 79 minutes.<ref name="soccerway2">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/07/18/switzerland/super-league/fc-zurich/bsc-young-boys-bern/2048162/|title=FC Zürich vs. BSC Young Boys - 18 July 2015 - Soccerway|publisher=soccerway.com|access-date=29 August 2015}}</ref>

===Borussia Mönchengladbach===
In June 2017, Zakaria signed a five-year contract with [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]]. He was transferred as a replacement for [[Mahmoud Dahoud]] who left the club for [[Borussia Dortmund]]. The transfer fee paid to Young Boys for Zakaria was reported as €10 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bis 2022: Zakaria unterschreibt in Gladbach|url=https://www.kicker.de/bis-2022_zakaria-unterschreibt-in-gladbach-679686/artikel|access-date=9 June 2017|work=kicker Online|date=9 June 2017|language=de}}</ref>
Zakaria scored a total of 11 goals in 125 appearances for Borussia Mönchengladbach.<ref name=":0"/>

===Juventus===
On 31 January 2022, with six months remaining on his contract, Zakaria moved to [[Serie A]] club [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] on a four-and-a-half-year contract,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|date=31 January 2022|title=OFFICIAL {{!}} Zakaria joins Juventus!|url=https://www.juventus.com/en/news/articles/official-zakaria-joins-juventus|access-date=31 January 2022|website=Juventus.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|publisher=[[Borussia Mönchengladbach]]|url=https://www.borussia.de/en/news/news/2022-01-31-denis-zakaria-moves-to-juventus|title=DENIS ZAKARIA MOVES TO JUVENTUS|date=31 January 2022|access-date=31 January 2022}}</ref> in a deal worth €8.6 million.<ref name=":0"/> On 6 February, Zakaria scored on his debut in the 61st minute, helping his side beat [[Hellas Verona F.C.|Hellas Verona]] 2–0.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Vlahovic and Zakaria score on Juventus debuts in Verona win|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/sport/vlahovic-and-zakaria-score-juventus-debuts-verona-win-2483021|access-date=6 February 2022|website=CNA|language=en|archive-date=20 September 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220920171605/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/sport/vlahovic-and-zakaria-score-juventus-debuts-verona-win-2483021|url-status=dead}}</ref>

====Loan to Chelsea====
On 1 September 2022, Zakaria was loaned to [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] until the end of the 2022–23 season with an option of a permanent transfer at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Zakaria goes on loan to Chelsea from Juventus |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/blues-bring-in-zakaria-on-loan |website=Chelsea F.C. |date=2 September 2022 }}</ref>
On 2 November 2022, Zakaria made his Chelsea debut in the club's final [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League group stage|UEFA Champions League group stage]] match, scoring the winning goal of a 2–1 victory against [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chelsea 2–1 Dinamo Zagreb |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63479244 |website=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2022 }}</ref>

===Monaco===
On 14 August 2023, Zakaria moved to [[Ligue 1]] club [[AS Monaco|Monaco]] on a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asmonaco.com/en/denis-zakaria-is-a-monegasque/|title=Denis Zakaria is a Monegasque!|publisher=AS Monaco|date=14 August 2023|access-date=14 August 2023}}</ref>

==International career==
Zakaria played for various Swiss youth national teams. He could have represented either [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], [[South Sudan national football team|South Sudan]] or [[DR Congo national football team|Congo]] at a senior level due to being born in Switzerland and having a Congolese mother and a South Sudanese father.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bernerzeitung.ch/sport/fussball/zackig/story/11694896|title = Zackig|newspaper =[[Berner Zeitung]]}}</ref>

Zakaria made his debut for the senior Switzerland national team in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] 2–1 loss to [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] on 28 May 2016.<ref name="ntdebut">{{cite news|title=Switzerland include three teenagers in final squad for Euro 2016|url=http://www.espnfc.com/switzerland/story/2883266/switzerland-include-three-teenagers-in-final-squad-for-euro-2016|access-date=9 June 2017|work=ESPN FC|date=30 May 2016}}</ref> He was part of the squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016 European Championships]].<ref name="ntdebut"/> Zakaria was included in the 23-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/amphtml/sports/dcunited/switzerland-opts-for-experience-in-world-cup-squad/2018/06/04/86572ee2-680a-11e8-a335-c4503d041eaf_story.html The Washington Post]{{dead link|date=June 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

In May 2019, Zakaria played in the [[2019 UEFA Nations League Finals]], where his team finished fourth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48191915|title = Pickford the hero in England shootout win|work = BBC Sport}}</ref> He was named in the 26-man Swiss squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|author=The Athletic Staff|title=Switzerland's full 26-man Euro 2020 squad|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4211030/2021/06/01/switzerlands-full-26-man-euro-2020-squad/|access-date=2 July 2021|website=The Athletic}}</ref> On 2 July 2021, he scored an [[own goal]] in the 8th minute of Switzerland's quarter-final match against [[Spain national football team|Spain]], which they went on to lose on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]]. His own goal was the fastest in European Championship history, breaking [[Wojciech Szczęsny]]’s record of 18 minutes vs Slovakia earlier in the same tournament until [[Donyell Malen]] broke the record in the next tournament with an own goal in the 6th minute during the Netherlands vs Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch video: Zakaria's own goal gifts Spain early lead in Euro 2020 QF against Switzerland|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/sports/watch-video-zakarias-own-goal-gifts-spain-early-lead-in-euro-2020-qf-against-switzerland|access-date=2 July 2021|website=Free Press Journal}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Due to his characteristics and playing style, Zakaria has been compared with former France international [[Patrick Vieira]] as well as [[Paul Pogba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/denis-zakaria-xhaka-pogba-vieira-gladbach-midfield-heartbeat-458266.jsp|title=Denis Xhaka-ria the new heartbeat of the Borussia Mönchengladbach midfield|publisher=bundesliga.com|access-date=5 September 2022|archive-date=5 September 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220905174516/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/denis-zakaria-xhaka-pogba-vieira-gladbach-midfield-heartbeat-458266.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> Zakaria has been described as a midfield powerhouse due to his pace, strength, athleticism and aggressive playing style.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/denis-zakaria-borussia-monchengladbach-midfielder-switzerland-monster-510260.jsp|title=Denis Zakaria: Borussia Mönchengladbach's midfield monster|publisher=bundesliga.com|access-date=5 September 2022|archive-date=5 September 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220905174517/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/denis-zakaria-borussia-monchengladbach-midfielder-switzerland-monster-510260.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref> He is also known for being a composed passer and for making surging forward runs from midfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/denis-zakaria-who-is-borussia-monchengladbach-and-switzerland-s-midfield-marvel-7905|title=Denis Zakaria: Who is Borussia Mönchengladbach and Switzerland's midfield marvel?|publisher=bundesliga.com|access-date= 5 September 2022}}</ref> Primarily a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], he is also capable of playing as a [[central midfielder]], in a [[Midfielder#Holding midfielder|holding role]], or a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box role]], and has even played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/denis-zakaria-the-biography|title=Denis Zakaria - the biography|work=chelseafc.com|date=2 September 2022|access-date=2 September 2022}}</ref>

